Halve, peel and chop the @Echalion Shallot{1} into roughly 1/2cm pieces. Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Remove the root and the dark green tops from the @Leek{1}, halve lengthways and slice into thin half moons. Twist and tear the @Flat Leaf Parsley{1%bunch} in half. Pick the parsley leaves from their stalks and roughly chop. Finely chop the stalks (keep them separate). Roughly chop the @Brazil Nuts{25}.

Pop your chopped parsley leaves in a small #bowl{} with your brazil nuts and the @Grated Hard Italian Style Cheese{40%g}. Add the @Olive Oil{4%tbsp}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{pinch} and mix together.

Heat a glug of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Add the @Gnocchi{300%g} and fry until it is golden and crispy, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> TIP: Make sure to stir the gnocchi to ensure all sides are crispy.

Meanwhile, put a large #saucepan{} on medium heat with a drizzle of oil and add the shallot and leek. Cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Next, add the garlic and parsley stalks. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @Tinned Plum Tomatoes{1%can} to your saucepan with the shallot and leek. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break them up. Add the @Water{100%ml} and stir in the @Vegetable Stock Pot{1/2}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot and bubble away for ~{7-8%minutes}.

Stir the @King Prawns{120%g} into the tomato sauce and cook for ~{7%minutes}.

> TIP: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque all the way through.

Add the prawn and tomato sauce to the gnocchi and stir together. Serve in #bowls{} with a few spoonfuls of brazil nut pesto on top. Enjoy!